1. Predicting Samsung Stock Prices Using LSTM¶

This project will predict the closing stock prices of Samsung using all kinds of RNN models, such as a

  • Univariate
  • Bidirectional
  • Stacked

LSTM model.

In [45]:
# create a function to process the data into a form that can be fed into the model

def create_dataset(dataset, look_back = 1):
	dataX, dataY = [], []
	for i in range(len(dataset) - look_back - 1):
		a = dataset[i:(i + look_back), 0]
		dataX.append(a)
		dataY.append(dataset[i + look_back, 0])
	return np.array(dataX), np.array(dataY)

def predict_and_score(model, X, Y):
    pred = scaler.inverse_transform(model.predict(X))
    orig_data = scaler.inverse_transform([Y])
    score = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(orig_data[0], pred[:, 0]))
    return (score, pred)

rmse_train, train_predict = predict_and_score(model, X_train, y_train)

3.3 Model Building (Stacked LSTM)¶

In [51]:
from keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping

def fit_model(train_X, train_Y, look_back=3):
    model = Sequential()
    
    model.add(LSTM(50, activation='relu', return_sequences=True, input_shape=(1, look_back)))
    model.add(LSTM(50, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(1))
    model.compile(loss = "mean_squared_error", 
                  optimizer = "adam")
    early_stopping =  EarlyStopping(patience=10,  restore_best_weights=True)
    model.fit(train_X, 
              train_Y, 
              epochs = 100, 
              batch_size = 1, 
              verbose = 1,
              callbacks=[early_stopping],
              validation_split=0.2)
    
    return model

model2 = fit_model(X_train, y_train, look_back)

3.4 Model Building (Bidirectional LSTM)¶

In [71]:
def fit_model(train_X, train_Y, look_back=3):
    model = Sequential()
    
    model.add(Bidirectional(LSTM(128, activation='relu', return_sequences=True, input_shape=(1, look_back))))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))
    model.add(Bidirectional(LSTM(64, activation='relu')))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))
    model.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(1))
    
    model.compile(loss="mean_squared_error", optimizer="adam")
    
    early_stopping = EarlyStopping(patience=15, restore_best_weights=True)
    
    model.fit(train_X, train_Y, epochs=100, batch_size=32, verbose=1, callbacks=[early_stopping], validation_split=0.2)

    return model

model3 = fit_model(X_train, y_train, look_back)

import csv
from datetime import datetime, timedelta

start_date = datetime(2022, 5, 24)
input_sequence = X_test[-look_back:]
input_sequence = np.reshape(input_sequence, (1, look_back, 1))

predictions = []
dates = []

for _ in range(30):
	next_prediction = model.predict(input_sequence)
	predictions.append(next_prediction[0, 0])
	
	input_sequence = np.append(input_sequence[:, 1:, :], np.expand_dims(next_prediction, axis=1), axis=1)

	start_date += timedelta(days=1)
	dates.append(start_date.strftime("%Y-%m-%d"))

predictions = scaler.inverse_transform([predictions])[0]

with open('predictions.csv', 'w', newline='') as file:
	writer = csv.writer(file)
	writer.writerow(['Date', 'Predicted Closing Price'])
	for date, prediction in zip(dates, predictions):
		writer.writerow([date, prediction])

print("Predictions saved to predictions.csv file.")
